A human rights groups say the South African government is not doing enough to protect Africans from other countries seeking refuge in the country. JOHANNESBURG A human rights groups say the South African government is not doing enough to protect Africans from other countries seeking refuge in the country. As the continent celebrates Africa Day today, there have been calls for South Africans to be more accepting of migrants. Amnesty International's Shenilla Mohamed says government should step up and take control of the situation. Foreigners become the scapegoat for what s happening on an economic, political and social level in a country.The African Diaspora Forum's Marc Gbaffou agrees. Many people, including some government officials like Herman Mashaba, who says people are illegal. People don t choose to be illegal. Governments should provide so that they re legal. (Edited by Shimoney Regter)